<subSubSection id="0A88F2D1FF94FF9AFF6DFB44FB65E4BF" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="description">
<paragraph id="422DA15AFF94FF9AFF6DFB44FB65E4BF" blockId="1.[151,1437,1108,1493]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
Two distinct â€˜ecomorphsâ€™ (in the original sense of 
<bibRefCitation id="2603DCABFF94FF9AFD57FB45FC10E596" author="Williams, E. E." box="[765,934,1252,1277]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" pagination="47 - 89" refId="ref28918" refString="Williams, E. E. (1972) The origin of faunas. Evolution of lizard congeners in a complex island fauna: a trial analysis. In: Dobzhansky, T., Hecht, M. K. &amp; Steere, W. C. (Eds.), Evolutionary Biology. Meredith Corporation, New York, pp. 47 - 89. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / 978 - 1 - 4684 - 9063 - 3 _ 3" type="book chapter" year="1972">Williams 1972</bibRefCitation>
: 82) occur within the genus, often at a single locality (Huber 2005): long-legged pale whitish to greenish spiders associated with live leaves where they build irregular or highly regular domed sheet webs with the apex in contact with the underside of the leaf; and shortlegged brownish spiders in the leaf litter, with tiny webs and possibly sometimes without webs. Molecular data suggest that there have been several shifts between live leaves and leaf litter within 
<taxonomicName id="8592DAD9FF94FF9AFBE4FAD5FA2EE4E6" authority="(Eberle et al. 2018)" authorityName="Eberle" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Eberle" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[1102,1432,1396,1421]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Belisana" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="70E67D48FF94FF9AFBE4FAD5FB06E4E7" box="[1102,1200,1396,1421]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Belisana</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2603DCABFF94FF9AFB6AFAD5FA27E4E6" author="Eberle, J. &amp; Dimitrov, D. &amp; Valdez-Mondragon, A. &amp; Huber, B. A." box="[1216,1425,1396,1421]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" pagination="141" refId="ref26630" refString="Eberle, J., Dimitrov, D., Valdez-Mondragon, A. &amp; Huber, B. A. (2018) Microhabitat change drives diversification in pholcid spiders. BMC Evolutionary Biology, 18, 141. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 12862 - 018 - 1244 - 8" type="journal article" year="2018">
Eberle 
<emphasis id="70E67D48FF94FF9AFAB9FAD4FAFAE4E7" box="[1299,1356,1396,1421]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Five of the six known Sri Lankan species (all treated below) belong to the long-legged ecomorph; the newly described 
